<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading"><span dir="auto">GPL Violations</span></h1>
 
 
<div id="bodyContent">
 
<div id="siteSub">From linux-sunxi.org</div>
 
 
<div id="contentSub"></div>
 
 
<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
Jump to: <a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, <a href="#p-search">search</a>
</div>
 
 
<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p><a href="/Allwinner" title="Allwinner">Allwinner</a> has repeatedly violated the <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://gnu.org/licenses/gpl">GPL</a> (and by proxy so have most hardware manufacturers and resellers using or selling products based on Allwinner chipsets). Either by not providing (Linux/Android) kernel or u-boot source at all, or by delivering trees with pre-built binaries and no matching source code. They even blatantly use <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://gnu.org/licenses/lgpl">LGPL</a> licensed code in their userspace libraries for media decoding.
</p><p>Over time, Allwinner has only increased the binary blobs present in their kernel trees, showing clearly that - even though Allwinner in the meantime joined <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://linaro.org">Linaro</a> - it is not progressing. Quite the opposite actually, and one has to worry about what value Linaro membership really has if a member is allowed to behave like this.
</p><p>Allwinner also <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.linuxfoundation.org/news-media/announcements/2015/06/new-linux-foundation-members-advance-open-source-enterprise">joined the Linux Foundation</a> as of June 2015, while compliance issues clearly remain.
</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc"><tr><td><div id="toctitle"><h2>Contents</h2></div>
<ul>
